White population represents the highest education seeker overall. They seem to attain High-school, associate degrees, Bacherlors, some college degrees and some Masters. Second is black population which represents High school, some college degree, Bachelor and even doctorate degrees. Third is Asian-pacific Islander which represents High school, some college degree and Bachelor degrees. The 'Other' race shows the least study pursued in Bacherlors, High school and some college degree.

Bias: In US, High school means 9th, 10, 11th and 12th but in this data, I see all of them as cateogries.¶

Q2. How is income correlating with different variables like education, workclass, occupation, race, marital status and sex?¶

In [23]:
# Analyze the impact of individual features on income using grouped bar plots
features_of_interest = ['Education', 'Workclass', 'Occupation', 'Race', 'Marital-status', 'Sex']

for feature in features_of_interest:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.countplot(x=feature, hue='Income', data=df, palette='viridis')
    plt.title(f'Income Distribution by {feature}')
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.show()

Income distribution by education¶

  • Based on education, this plot tells us that people who earned high school graduate, some college and bachelors degrees (top 3) earned <=50k income. Higher education does show higher income.
  • However, people who earned a Doctorate and Prof-school earned >50k income.
  • There are less number of people who earned 5-6th, 10th, 1st-4th, preschool, and 12th class earned <=50k.

Income distribution by Workclass¶

  • People who worked in the private sector have the highest regardless of earning <=50k or >50k.
  • Other high categories are self-employed-not inc, Unknown sector, State-gov, local-gov, self-emp-inc and federal-gov sectors.
  • There is no data available in the Without-pay and Never-worked categories.

Income distribution by Occupation¶

  • A majority of people have <50k income based on sector.
  • The most commonly occurring occupations in both income categories are executive-managerial and professional-specialty. Except for armed forces and private-house-serve sector <=50k are high in all occupation sector.

Income distribution by Race¶

  • White represents very high income slab than the rest.

Income distribution by Marital status¶

  • The people who are never married represent the highest and have <=50k income
  • The people who are married-civilian-spouse represent the second highest have <=50k income. They also have a high income with >50k which may conclude the combined salary of spouse.

Income distribution by Sex¶

  • Male has more earning than female.
  • Male earns <=50k than >50k.
  • Female earns <=50k than >50k.

People who worked in the private sector have the highest regardless of earning <=50k or >50k.

US income distribution by Occupation¶

A majority of people have <50k income based on sector. The most commonly occurring occupations in both income categories are executive-managerial and professional-specialty. Except for armed forces and private-house-serve sector <=50k are high in all occupation sector.

US income distribution by Race¶

White race represents the highest income with <=50k and >50k

US income distribution by Marital status¶

Other countries Based on education, this plot tells us that people who earned high school graduate, some college, bachelors degrees and school 5-6th 7-8th class education are coming into the picture with salary of <=50k.

Income distribution by Workclass People who worked in the private sector have the highest regardless of earning <=50k or >50k.

Occupation craft repair, other services, and prof-specialty are showing high trends with <=50k income.

Race White race represents the highest income with <=50k and >50k followed by Asian-Pac-Islander group.

Income distribution by Marital status Never Married and Married-civ-spouse are both showing high trends with <=50k income.

Income distribution by Sex

  • Male has more earning than female.
  • Male earns more of <=50k than >50k.
  • Female earns <=50k than >50k but this trend is better than US country.

Limitations in this dataset¶

  • Little data on capital gains and loss to be analysed with income.
  • Couldn't perform median or average and replace in any column as they represent the country dataset. It is possible when data is at state level.

Conclusion¶

  • Similar trends of high private jobs, occupation and income range in US population and other countries.
  • Male population having more income than females.
  • The median age of >50k income is 45 years.
  • White population has high frequency of some college, HS-grad and Bachelors degree.
  • Not much difference in pattern of analysis between US and other countries. It is noticeable to say that 80% of world census data is coming from the US.
